  { :name => "GF Career | CityWIDE Professional Dance Classes | Presented by gloATL", :longitude => -84.41622559999999, :latitude => 33.7862277, :gmaps => true, :description => "Ongoing \n\nSchedule of Classes:  http://gloatl.org/citywide-class-schedule/\n\nCityWIDE was created to support the emerging and professional dance/performance artists in Atlanta with an affordable \"city     wide\" dance class geared towards atlanta's various performance based platforms. CityWIDE aims to establish an environment where visiting artists can feel welcome and local artists can feel at home.\n\nPresented by gloATL\n\nAs part of \"Stimulus Diffusion\", the Goat Farm's Career Development & Education Platform\n\nContact gloATL for schedule & details:  info@gloatl.com\n\nGoodson Yard at the Goat Farm Arts Center\n1200 Foster Street\nAtlanta, GA 30318\n\nLocation can change due to temperature. Please check links below for updated location and schedule.\n\nFacebook:  (https://www.facebook.com/pages/City-WIDE/275176532509864?sk=wall)\n\nSchedule of Classes:  http://gloatl.org/citywide-class-schedule/\n\nRate: $5 per class for professionals and college students\n$10 for all other drop-ins\n\nAll money goes directly to the teacher, so that we can cover the cost of a quality teacher. Please cash only.\n\n__________________________________________________________________\n\nSCHEDULE::\n\nThe classes will be Tuesday-Saturday covering a variety of styles including contemporary, ballet and yoga. The schedule will vary weekly, so we'll post updates. Check out City WIDE's facebook page every Monday for the weekly schedule. \n\nThe classes are part of Stimulus Diffusion, the Goat Farm’s new support platform for creative education and career development. \n\nThrough Stimulus Diffusion, the Goat Farm is aggregating partners in one convenient location at the Arts Center to create a dense curriculum. \n\nOur hope is that by having this large network of educational affiliates in one locale we can begin to find synergies and marketing advantages. We want to inform people of the growing number of educational initiatives at the Goat Farm. \n\n", :start_time => "2017-01-01 10:00:00", :end_time => "2017-01-01 11:00:00", :address => "1200 Foster St NW, Atlanta, GA 30318, USA", :fb_id => 453728948012413, :owner_id => 162337850449783, :city => nil, :country => nil, :picture => "https://fbcdn-profile-a.akamaihd.net/hprofile-ak-snc6/276850_453728948012413_130738751_q.jpg", :atenders => 14, :privacy => nil, :created_at => "2012-11-15 05:25:05", :updated_at => "2012-11-15 05:25:05" },
  { :name => "Tanz Farm | A Performance Anthology | Curated by gloATL & the Goat Farm | Series 4 of 4", :longitude => -84.41622559999999, :latitude => 33.7862277, :gmaps => true, :description => "The Goat Farm Arts Center Presents:\n\nTanz Farm – A Performance Anthology\nCurated by gloATL & The Goat Farm\n\nTANZ FARM SERIES 4\n\n___________________________________________________________\nSummer Performance Series\nMay 9-11, 2013\nin the Goodson Yard Performance Hall\nat The Goat Farm Arts Center\n1200 Foster Street\nAtlanta GA 30318\n_ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _\nARTISTS:\nAmanda Miller (GER) Choreographer\n\nCORE Performance (ATL)\n\n_ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _\n\nTICKETS:\n$25 General Admisssion $15 Artists/Students\nSeason subscription: All 4 Performacnces $80\n\nPURCHASE TICKETS:\nhttp://www.ticketalternative.com/SitePages/Search.aspx?catid=All&pattern=tanz\n_ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _\n\nSCHEDULE:\n\nMay 9-11, 2013 (3 performances)\n\nThursday-Saturday 8pm\n\n___________________________________________________________\n___________________________________________________________\n\nSummer Initiatives:\nall initiatives are Free & Open to the Public\n\nShop| Artists to Artists series\nSaturday, April 27, 2013 | 1030-12noon | Amanda Miller\n_ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _\n\nFeed| Artists Talk\nSaturday, May 11, 2013 | 12noon-130\n_ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _\n\nWIP| Works in Process\nThursday, May 2, 2013 | 7pm\n\n_ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _\n\nLiv | Artist Residencies in Goodson Yard at The Goat Farm\n\nApril 22-May 11, 2013\nAmanda Miller / CORE Performance\n___________________________________________________________\n___________________________________________________________\nArtists’ Biographies:\n\nAmerican born choreographer Amanda Miller has been dancing and choreographing throughout her career, in wonderful places like North Carolina School of the Arts, Ballet Frankfurt, and Netherlands Dans Theater, to name a few. She is the founding artist of Germany’s Pretty Ugly Dance Company, that for 20 years has provided a platform for dancers, musicians, and artists of other related mediums to create works free from the norms of traditional theaters and budgets. Since it was formed, Pretty Ugly Dance Company has toured works throughout the U.S, Europe, Japan, and India, and continues to develop works of art based on influences of collaboration between the art forms.\n\n_ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _\n\nSince 1980, CORE Performance Company has been creating and performing innovative contemporary dance. Known for its riveting, passionate and unique work, CORE has been internationally acclaimed in performance, tours and residencies in the U.S., Mexico, Guatemala, Sweden, Germany, Croatia and the Republic of Georgia.  With homes in Atlanta, Georgia and Houston, Texas, CORE creates intimate and original work that evolves through experimentation, improvisation, and collaboration with artists from different mediums.  Performing the work of Artistic Director, Sue Schroeder, as well as guest choreographers including Beppie Blankert, Polly Motley, Alicia Sánchez, Ellen Bromberg, Bill Evans, Jacalyn Carley, Tanzcompagnie Rubato, Bill Young and John Mead, CORE maintains a strong profile as a contemporary dance company through its diverse body of multi-layered work.\n", :start_time => "2013-05-09 20:00:00", :end_time => "2013-05-11 23:00:00", :address => "1200 Foster St NW, Atlanta, GA 30318, USA", :fb_id => 491862187490866, :owner_id => 155914407878678, :city => nil, :country => nil, :picture => "https://fbcdn-profile-a.akamaihd.net/hprofile-ak-ash4/211179_491862187490866_1771308370_q.jpg", :atenders => 20, :privacy => nil, :created_at => "2012-11-15 05:25:10", :updated_at => "2012-11-15 05:25:10" },
  { :name => "Tanz Farm: a Performance Anthology| Performance series III:spring/ Hippodrome: World Premiere|| The Atlanta Opera\\Lauri Stallings &gloATL/Gyun Hur/Sonic Generator Music Ensemble", :longitude => -84.41622559999999, :latitude => 33.7862277, :gmaps => true, :description => "Tanz Farm: a Performance Anthology Inaugural Season\ncurated by gloATL & The Goat Farm\n\nPerformances Experiments and Shops emphasizing sociability, experience and conversation\nTANZ FARM Performance Series III: spring\n\nHippodrome, A World Premiere\nA new creation in concert with artists whose mediums are opera, dance, sculpture, music and non-traditional \nperformance space used as a place for being together.\n\nARTISTS:\nThe Atlanta Opera (ATL\nLauri Stallings & gloATL(ATL)\nGyun Hur (ATL)\nSonic Generator Music Ensemble\n\nTICKETS:\n$25 General Admisssion $15 Artists/Students\nSeason subscription: All 4 Performacnces $80\n\nPURCHASE TICKETS: http://www.ticketalternative.com/SitePages/Search.aspx?catid=All&pattern=tanz\n_ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _\nPerformance SCHEDULE:\n\nThursday March 14- Sunday March 24, 2013 8pm \n(Sunday at 3pm)\n8 performances Only\n______________________________________________________\nArtists’ Biographies:\n\nFounded in 1979, The Atlanta Opera is one of the finest regional opera companies in the nation, drawing audiences from the entire metropolitan Atlanta area as well as from the Southeast region.  The Atlanta Opera strives to expand the experience of its patrons with memorable and exciting opera performances reflecting the highest musical and theatrical standards, while supporting community and educational programs.  The company also works to attract the finest international, national, and regional singers, conductors, stage directors and designers.  Each season The Atlanta Opera presents three productions with four performances each at the Cobb Energy Centre.\n __________________________________________________________\ngloATL is a collaborative platform of exceptional contemporary physical experience, founded in July, 2009 by choreographer Lauri Stallings.  gloATL’s mission is to create exceptional art through live performance, public works, and a choreographic LAB. gloATL’s work increasingly shares a synergy with art forms, blending classical elements with the complexity and groove of today’s rhythmic culture. Part choreography and part interactive art installation, gloATL performances regularly bridge the gap between artists and audience, to explore fundamentals found in philosophies of relational aesthetics, such as being together, voluntary migration, and the inter-human. In Stallings' work is a vivid line which refers to the whereabouts of mankind’s existence.\n\n_ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _\n\nGyun Hur was born in Daegu, Korea. She came to the United States at the age of thirteen and her experience of relocating into a different culture has impacted artist’s making. The artist explores geographical and cultural placeness through projects incorporating sculpture, installation, and performance art.\n\nGyun Hur has performed and exhibited in Atlanta, New York City, Chicago, Seattle, and China. Gyun completed New York City residency through Elizabeth’s Foundation for the Arts in 2009. She attended Vermont Studio Center, Ox-Bow Artist-in-Residence, and Virginia Center for the Creative Arts. She is the recipient of The Hudgens Prize, Artadia Award, and Joan Mitchell Foundation Scholarship. Her works have been reviewed in Art in America, Sculpture, Art Paper, Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Creative Loafing and The Atlantan.\n\nShe currently lives and works in Atlanta. Gyun enjoys to travel, read, eat strawberry ice cream, and play with her puppy Choco.\n\n_ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _\n\nFounded in 2006, Sonic Generator is the contemporary music ensemble-in-residence at Georgia Tech dedicated to using technology to transform the ways in which we compose, perform, and listen to music.  The group works closely with students and faculty across campus to implement technology in concert and to incorporate new research into live performance.\n\nSonic Generator presents a diverse lineup of music by composers such as Steve Reich, John Cage, Mario Davidovsky, Brian Eno, Louis Andriessen, and Terry Riley; it is also committed to performing music of younger composers and to commissioning new works. Sonic Generator’s experiments with new technologies have led the group to perform with wine glasses, iPhones, comic strips, car speakers, DJs, and a robotic drummer. The ensemble also frequently collaborates with visual artists to create video projections to accompany its performances.\n\nSonic Generator’s work has been recognized by the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, which noted that the group was “…the most stimulating addition to Atlanta’s musical life…” in its debut season. Inside Arts, a national trade magazine for arts presenters, featured the group’s innovative work with video on its front cover. Sonic Generator has performed at national conferences of the College Music Society and the Society of Composers, and its concerts at Georgia Tech routinely attract a standing-room-only crowd.\n_ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _\n\nTian Justman\n\n©", :start_time => "2013-03-14 20:00:00", :end_time => "2013-03-24 17:00:00", :address => "1200 Foster St NW, Atlanta, GA 30318, USA", :fb_id => 261971667257098, :owner_id => 155914407878678, :city => nil, :country => nil, :picture => "https://fbcdn-profile-a.akamaihd.net/hprofile-ak-snc6/276857_261971667257098_879476494_q.jpg", :atenders => 26, :privacy => nil, :created_at => "2012-11-15 05:25:16", :updated_at => "2012-11-15 05:25:16" },
  { :name => "Tanz Farm: a Performance Anthology | Performance Series 2: Winter| zoe/juniper/Seattle|Staib Dance/ATL| Gustavo Rimerez Sansano/Chicago|curated by gloATL & The Goat Farm Arts Center", :longitude => -84.41622559999999, :latitude => 33.7862277, :gmaps => true, :description => "Tanz Farm: a Performance Anthology Inaugural Season\nCurated by gloATL & The Goat Farm\nPerformances Experiments and Shops emphasizing sociability, experience and conversation\n\nTANZ FARM Performance series II: Winter\nzoe/juniper/Seattle| Staib Dance/Atlanta|Gustavo Rimerez Sansano/Luna Negra Dance Theater/Chicago\n\nFriday-Sunday December 14-16 at 8pm (Sunday at 3pm)\nGoodson Yard Performance Hall\nat The Goat Farm Arts Center\n1200 Foster Street\nAtlanta GA 30318\nwww.tanzfarm.com\n\nTICKETS:\n$25 General Admisssion $15 Artists/Students\nSeason subscription: All 4 Performances $80\n\nPURCHASE TICKETS HERE:\nhttp://ticketalternative.com/SitePages/Search.aspx?catid=All&pattern=Gustavo\nARTISTS: \n\nzoe/juniper (Seattle) | new creation for gloATL\nA Taste | http://vimeo.com/44625565\n\nStaib Dance (Atlanta): new creation\nA Taste | http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q4Hm58v-Drw\n\nGustavo Rimerez Sansano/Luna Negra: repertoire work\nA Taste | http://vimeo.com/29588854\n___________________________________________________________\nArtists' Biographies:\n\nZoe/Juniper:\nZoe/Juniper (Seattle) are drawn together as collaborators by their respect for and subverted use of classical form, aesthetic clarity and the desire to create a sense of heightened reality.\n \nZoe Scofield and Juniper Shuey began their collaboration in 2004 with; I am nothing without you, for On the Boards’ NW New Works Festival 2005. Spectrum Dance Theater, the Frye Art Museum and Ten Tiny Dances have commissioned the in company 2007, 2008 and 2009 respectively.\n\nThey received a NPN Creation Fund and Residency commission, and a National Dance Project Production Grant (2008-2009) for their work the devil you know is better than the devil you don’t.. zoe | juniper are recipients of an Artist Trust Fellowship and GAP grant and received a National Dance Project Production. \nA Crack in Everything premiered in 2011 at Jacob’s Pillow and will tour throughout 2013. \n\n_ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _\n\nGeorge Staib/Staib Dance:\nSince its debut in 2007, Atlanta-based, Staibdance has produced five concerts including an evening-length collaboration with the internationally acclaimed Vega String Quartet in February of 2009. \n\nThe Atlanta Journal-Constitution called the performance “magnetic, tense and euphoric – like romance itself” and hailed the choreography as “bold and kinetic” and “seamlessly tuned to the music.”  \nFollowing the success of that performance, Staibdance was produced at the annual Big Range Festival at the Barnevelder Theater in Houston, Texas.  \n\nReviewer Neil Ellis Orts of Dance Source Houston praised Staib for his “strong command of a diverse movement vocabulary and [his] gift for large-cast dances.”  Staibdance was also a proud participant at the Cobb Energy Center’s Overture to  the Arts in the fall of 2009.\n\n_ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _\n\n Gustavo Ramirez Sansano (Spain) was appointed Artistic Director of Luna Negra Dance Theater in 2009, after directing TITOYAYA Dance Project in Valencia, Spain for the last four years. Sansano has been the recipient of numerous awards for his choreography, including first prizes at the Ricard Moragas competition in Barcelona, the Dom Perignon choreographic competition in Hamburg, and at Las Artes Escénicas de la Comunidad Valenciana.\n \nHis work has been featured at “Les Etoiles de Ballet” in Cannes, and the IX International Festival of Ballet in Miami. He has been commissioned to create works for Compania Nacional de Danza, the Hamburg Ballet, Budapest Dance Theater, Ballet Junior de Genève, and Nederlands Dans Theater II, among others. \n\nAs a dancer, Sansano performed works by Jacopo Godani, Hans Van Manen, Jiří Kylián, Ohad Naharin, Johan Inger, Paul Lightfoot, Victor Ullate and many more, working for the Ballet Joven de Alicante, Ballet Contemporaneo de Barcelona, Ballet de la Comunidad de Madrid, Nederlands Dans Theater II and Hubbard Street Dance Chicago.\n\n_ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _\n\nKlimchak\n\nKlimchak specializes in electro-acoustic music for theater, dance and live solo performance. He is the winner of the 2009 Loridans Arts Award, a $15,000 cash prize given to \"accomplished artists who have made exceptional contributions to the arts life of Atlanta\" or as it's often called, \"Atlanta's MacArthur Genius Award.\" Klimchak's 2009 score for Titus Andronicus at Ga Shakespeare won a Suzi Award for best sound design. His homebuilt instruments & performances were displayed in 2010 in the art show Limitless at Agnes Scott College.\n\nIn January 2011, Klimchak was given a grant by Idea Capital to design & make some new percussion instruments & compose music for them. These will be performed in 2011-2012 by a group of 4 musicians as flash percussion performances, in a series titled Klimchak's Lebeato Lounge.\n\nAs a solo performer, Klimchak gives shows in clubs and alternative spaces, which feature his talents on the amazing Don Buchla Marimba Lumina. With the Marimba Lumina Klimchak is able to perform live music that would normally take at least 4 musicians. His multi-instrumental compositions are played with 4 separate mallets, six foot pedals and a breath controller. As added touches, his sets usually include 4 or 5 small percussion instruments, ethnic wind instruments, and some chanting or tuvan throat singing. And on a good evening he'll also add in some theremin to the mix.\n\n_ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _\n\nTanz Farm: a Performance Anthology\nInaugural Season\nwww.tanzfarm.com\n\nfor more information write us at info@tanzfarm.com\n\ngloATL and The Goat Farm Arts Center\n", :start_time => "2012-12-14 20:00:00", :end_time => "2012-12-16 17:00:00", :address => "1200 Foster St NW, Atlanta, GA 30318, USA", :fb_id => 156460814491476, :owner_id => 155914407878678, :city => nil, :country => nil, :picture => "https://fbcdn-profile-a.akamaihd.net/hprofile-ak-ash4/373478_156460814491476_746193463_q.jpg", :atenders => 42, :privacy => nil, :created_at => "2012-11-15 05:25:21", :updated_at => "2012-11-15 05:25:21" },
  { :name => "glo's Aqua Art Miami debut:The Dress Rehearsal for Atlanta", :longitude => 9.134229999999999, :latitude => 47.046, :gmaps => true, :description => "3-year old Atlanta-based contemporary platform gloATL is making its International Fair debut at Aqua Art Fair during Art Basel 2012, with glo's founding artist Lauri Stallings' \n\nLivers:REMIX a physical Exhibition \nOn a Theme of Endurance.\n\nAqua Art/Art Basel Premiere: Wednesday December 5 \n7-10pm  thru Friday, December 7th!\n____________________________________________________________\nFor those of you who can't come with us, we are having \n\nTHE DRESS REHEARSAL FOR ATLANTA\nSaturday December 1 8-10pm in Goodson Yard\n\nAqua Art says, \"This year, visitors to Aqua12 will also be able to experience a uniquely comprehensive arts programming, at the core of which is the work of Atlanta-based artist Lauri Stallings and her performance art troupe Glo. Livers: REMIX is a 4-hour continuous work that conducts an entire precarious world between the performers and the city of Miami Beach. It begins at Aqua as a physical installation of choreographed gestures in a state of being together, and continues in migratory form along the pedestrian arteries of Collins Avenue, for a highly physical contemporary performance in a public space, sculpted as an 'arena of exchange.'\"\n____________________________________________________________\n\nLivers: REMIX Dress Rehearsal for Atlanta\nSaturday, December 1 8-10pm \n\nThe 4-hour exhibition will be trimmed to 2 hours for our city, come immerse yourself in this \"situationists\" world.\n\nAlso serving:\n\nMulled Wine\nRoasted nuts\nCherry Tarts\nand Livers!\n\nSuggested Donation at Door: $10. \n_________________________________________________________\n*Original Premiere Flux Projects October 2011, Atlanta.\n*a Possible Futures commission.\n\nwww.gloATL.org\nwww.aquaartmiami.com\n\n\n", :start_time => "2012-12-01 20:00:00", :end_time => "2012-12-01 22:00:00", :address => "Bulstern, 8765 Glarus Süd, Switzerland", :fb_id => 531343613560591, :owner_id => 203176429706691, :city => nil, :country => nil, :picture => "https://fbcdn-profile-a.akamaihd.net/hprofile-ak-ash4/373121_531343613560591_1115580247_q.jpg", :atenders => 39, :privacy => nil, :created_at => "2012-11-15 05:25:27", :updated_at => "2012-11-15 05:25:27" },
  { :name => "Drinks and Friends to Support WonderRoot and Burnaway", :longitude => -87.6461491, :latitude => 41.24114489999999, :gmaps => true, :description => "Join WonderRoot, Burnaway, SEEK ATL and friends for a casual evening of drinks and conversation at Octane - Grant Park.  That's right, our pals over at Octane are donating a portion of the proceeds from the evening to support WonderRoot and Burnaway's programs.  Just come on by anytime between 5pm and midnight and have a couple of drinks, a snack and talk to your pals.", :start_time => "2012-11-17 17:00:00", :end_time => "2012-11-17 23:45:00", :address => "200-252 W Taylor St, Grant Park, IL 60940, USA", :fb_id => 386504504763590, :owner_id => 1276656094, :city => nil, :country => nil, :picture => "https://fbcdn-profile-a.akamaihd.net/hprofile-ak-ash4/592194_386504504763590_1166298941_q.jpg", :atenders => 67, :privacy => nil, :created_at => "2012-11-15 05:25:32", :updated_at => "2012-11-15 05:25:32" },
  { :name => "What's Under There", :longitude => -84.3879824, :latitude => 33.7489954, :gmaps => true, :description => "Zoetic Dance Ensemble presents What’s Under There, a new work inspired by Laurel Nakadate: Photographs, Videos & Performances at the Atlanta Contemporary Art Center on November 15 from 6:30 – 8pm.\n\nWhat’s Under There is a performance incorporating dancers’ voices, bodies and experiences set among the hauntingly beautiful photographs from Nakadate’s 365 Days: A Catalogue of Tears, a rigorous photographic performance during which the artist documented herself crying each day. What’s Under There is interactive, allowing the audience to determine what it is that is being revealed, and and the chance to move their bodies to the music. \n\nWhat’s Under There is created in collaboration with Zoetic’s creative partners Melanie Lynch-Blanchard and Amanda Thompson. The process has been an interesting exercise for Zoetic, a dance company focused on women, collaboration and creating new work. Director Melanie Lynch-Blanchard explains, “We were inspired by Nakadate’s ability to draw the audience in as a collaborator, which is something we strive for in performance. Zoetic’s work shifts from beautiful to humorous to disturbing, which is a quality present in Nakadate’s work as well. And we share a fascination with panties.”  \n\nWhat’s Under There: November 15th from 6:30 to 8pm at the Atlanta Contemporary Art Center at 535 Means St. in Atlanta.  Galleries open at 6:30pm followed by the performance at 7. Admission is free as part of the Contemporary’s Free Thursdays program, sponsored by IntownAPARTMENTS.com by Perennial.  Laurel Nakadate: Photographs, Videos & Performances, curated by the Contemporary’s Artistic Director Stuart Horodner, is on view through December 6th. For details visit http://www.thecontemporary.org/.\n", :start_time => "2012-11-15 18:30:00", :end_time => "2012-11-15 20:00:00", :address => "214 Capitol Pl SW, Atlanta, GA 30303, USA", :fb_id 